 {"id":"asupersync-37g8j","title":"Trace/metrics handle audit (read-mostly path)","description":"Goal: audit trace + metrics handle access on hot paths and recommend the lightest-weight locking strategy without altering deterministic trace ordering.\n\nScope:\n- TraceBufferHandle usage in worker/scheduler paths (seq allocation + event emission).\n- MetricsProvider access (read-mostly) in state and task completion.\n- Identify any unnecessary locking or cloning to eliminate during sharding.\n\nDeliverables:\n- Recommendation: lock-free/Arc, RwLock, or dedicated lightweight mutex for trace/metrics handles.\n- Invariants required to keep deterministic trace order intact (sequence allocation, event ordering).\n- A small regression test or harness that validates trace ordering and metric emission do not change with sharding (deterministic seed + structured logs).\n- Guidance for bd-3xvow and docs bead (bd-3cza0) on where these handles should live.\n\nAcceptance:\n- Documented guidance in bead notes + linked to docs bead (bd-3cza0).\n- Test produces structured logs with seed, trace event count, and metric snapshots.","notes":"Audit complete. TraceBufferHandle and MetricsProvider can both be safely extracted from the Mutex. Findings added to docs/runtime_state_contention_inventory.md. Key: next_seq() is lock-free (AtomicU64), push_event() has internal Mutex, metrics are Arc+atomics. No shard lock needed for Shard D. Determinism preserved in Lab mode.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"FuchsiaCliff","created_at":"2026-02-04T19:55:42.627423735Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-04T21:05:17.169108976Z","closed_at":"2026-02-04T20:21:48.633826724Z","external_ref":"bd-12389","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-37g8j","depends_on_id":"asupersync-16z3x","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:44Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-37g8j","depends_on_id":"asupersync-zsiif","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:44Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1311,"issue_id":"asupersync-37g8j","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Determinism considerations:\n- TraceBufferHandle ordering must remain consistent with existing sequencing; any refactor must not reorder trace pushes or change sequence allocation.\n- Metrics are read-mostly; prefer lock-free read paths or RwLock with read dominance.\n- Avoid adding synchronization that could change interleaving in lab runs (especially around trace emission).","created_at":"2026-02-04T20:08:37Z"}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-37gf6","title":"[AA][Cap] Ambient authority audit + hardening","description":"## Goal\nAudit the entire codebase for ambient authority (implicit IO/time/random/spawn).\n\n## Why\nHidden effects break determinism and security. Every effect must flow through explicit capabilities.\n\n## Deliverables\n- Audit checklist + grep patterns.\n- Fixes for any ambient effects.\n- Regression tests to prevent reintroduction.\n\n## Acceptance\n- No ambient authority remains in core runtime.\n- New violations are caught by CI.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-03T00:09:29.456817845Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-03T03:59:44.582959700Z","closed_at":"2026-02-03T03:59:44.582885202Z","close_reason":"Audit complete in src/audit/ambient.rs with KNOWN_FINDINGS array + CI grep patterns. Found 8 non-exempt violations (3 time, 4 spawn, 2 entropy) and 5 exempt (by design). Added 2 missing spawn violations (server/connection.rs, http/h1/stream.rs). All effects in core runtime flow through Cx capabilities. Regression prevention via GREP_PATTERNS const for CI.","external_ref":"bd-3uag","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-37gf6","depends_on_id":"asupersync-b0l5n","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:09Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-37gf6","depends_on_id":"asupersync-wohz8","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:09Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-37hwj","title":"[EPIC-PHASE] Phase 1 - Parallel Scheduler and Region Heap","description":"## Overview\nPhase 1 extends the single-threaded deterministic kernel (Phase 0) to support parallel execution with work-stealing, region-isolated heaps, and multi-threaded scheduling while preserving all invariants.\n\n## Goals\n1. Enable true parallelism for throughput\n2. Maintain determinism in lab runtime (parallel simulation)\n3. Implement region heap for memory isolation\n4. Work-stealing scheduler for load balancing\n5. All Phase 0 invariants MUST be preserved\n\n## Key Components\n\n### 1. Work-Stealing Scheduler\n- Per-worker local queues\n- Global steal queue for overflow\n- Lock-free deque implementation\n- Maintain scheduling determinism via virtual schedule in lab mode\n\n### 2. Region Heap\n- Each region owns its allocations\n- Mass deallocation on region close\n- Thread-safe allocation within region\n- Region-local bump allocator (fast path)\n- Fallback to global allocator\n\n### 3. Parallel Task Model\n- `Task<T>` is `Send` - can migrate between workers\n- Wake deduplication across threads\n- Atomic task state transitions\n- Thread-safe RegionRecord access\n\n### 4. Synchronization Primitives (Parallel Versions)\n- Lock-free MPSC queue\n- Sharded counters for obligations\n- Atomic region state machine\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires complete Phase 0 kernel\n- Requires all Phase 0 invariants proven/tested\n- Requires two-phase primitives from Phase 0\n\n## Constraints\n- No additional invariants beyond Phase 0\n- Must support lab runtime schedule replay\n- Must support deterministic parallel simulation\n- Cannot break cancel-correctness\n\n## Non-Goals for Phase 1\n- I/O integration (Phase 2)\n- Actor model (Phase 3)\n- Distributed execution (Phase 4)\n- DPOR/TLA+ tooling (Phase 5)\n\n## Mathematical Foundation\nFrom the spec:\n- Work-stealing preserves eventual quiescence\n- Region heap uses arena allocation semantics\n- Parallel near-semiring: join/race laws still hold under parallelism\n\n## Testing Strategy\n- All Phase 0 tests must pass\n- Add parallel stress tests\n- Add work-stealing correctness tests\n- Verify determinism under parallel lab runtime\n\n## References\n- asupersync_plan_v4.md: §7 Phase 1 (Parallel)\n- Chase-Lev work-stealing deque\n- Region-based memory management (Tofte-Talpin)\n\n## Success Criteria\n- Parallel scheduler executes `Send` tasks across multiple workers while preserving Phase 0 invariants.\n- Region heap enables safe region-owned allocation and quiescent reclamation on close.\n- Lab runtime can deterministically *simulate* multi-worker schedules (repeatable traces).\n- Stress/E2E tests cover work stealing, cancellation drain, and quiescence under contention.\n","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"epic","assignee":"IvoryCompass","created_at":"2026-01-16T06:37:43.374776731Z","created_by":"Dicklesworthstone","updated_at":"2026-01-28T23:17:42.208110171Z","closed_at":"2026-01-28T23:17:42.207980400Z","external_ref":"bd-xrc","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-37hwj","depends_on_id":"asupersync-24my2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:19Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
+{"id":"asupersync-37j9k","title":"[audit][dns] Remove ambient Cx fallback from Resolver timeout and blocking dispatch","description":"src/net/dns/resolver.rs currently uses Cx::current() as an ambient fallback in default_timeout_now() and spawn_blocking_dns(). That makes Resolver timeout semantics and blocking dispatch depend on whichever context happens to be current at poll time, violating explicit-capability rules and risking mixed wall/virtual time bases across polls. Replace the ambient fallback with explicit resolver-owned defaults, keep deterministic/custom time_getter behavior intact, preserve non-runtime fallback execution for DNS/connect work, and add focused regressions proving resolver timeouts and blocking dispatch no longer depend on ambient Cx presence.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","assignee":"PurpleFox","created_at":"2026-03-10T23:38:27.831277581Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-10T23:54:33.146763389Z","closed_at":"2026-03-10T23:54:33.146739675Z","close_reason":"Implemented with targeted resolver validations green; repo-wide all-targets reruns launched but shared frontier still active","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"asupersync-37mz4","title":"Proof: Cancellation Terminates Under Budget","description":"Prove bounded termination of cancellation protocol using a Lyapunov/potential argument (Σ obligations + pending finalizers + remaining budget).\nShow that under sufficient budgets, cancel→drain→finalize terminates and cannot livelock.\nAcceptance: proof + bound statement that is checkable in tests (upper bound on steps/polls).","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"MaroonElk","created_at":"2026-02-03T18:01:41.221802010Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-04T05:28:26.957798877Z","closed_at":"2026-02-04T05:28:26.957724098Z","close_reason":"All acceptance criteria met: Lyapunov cancel_potential function, constructive cancel_protocol_terminates theorem (mask+3 steps by induction), cancel_steps_testable_bound (max 67 steps with MAX_MASK_DEPTH=64), plus termination from all mid-protocol states.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-37mz4","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1dbg2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:13Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-37mz4","depends_on_id":"asupersync-2oe02","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:13Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-37mz4","depends_on_id":"asupersync-6r78u","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:13Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-37o9s","title":"Define and implement Policy for region outcome aggregation","description":"# Policy (Region Outcome Aggregation + Escalation)\n\n## Purpose\nThe runtime needs a *policy surface* that defines how a region responds to child outcomes and how it computes its own terminal outcome.\n\nThis is essential for:\n- region close semantics\n- join semantics (⊗)\n- fail-fast behavior (cancel siblings on error)\n- later supervision/actors (Phase 3)\n\n## What Policy Must Decide (Phase 0)\n### 1) Outcome aggregation\nGiven:\n- outcomes of child tasks\n- outcomes of child regions\n- outcomes of finalizers (if modeled as tasks)\n\nCompute region outcome.\n\nDefault rule (from spec): **max severity wins** under the lattice:\n`Ok < Err < Cancelled < Panicked`.\n\n### 2) Response to child failure during execution (not only at close)\nWe need at least one policy suitable for Phase 0:\n- `Policy::default()` (no fail-fast; region closes normally)\n- `Policy::fail_fast()` (on first Err or Panicked, request cancellation of siblings)\n\nThis connects directly to join/race correctness.\n\n### 3) Monotonicity\nPolicy decisions must be monotone:\n- new information cannot downgrade the “worst” outcome already observed.\n\n## Plan-of-Record API\n```rust\n#[derive(Clone, Debug)]\npub struct Policy {\n    pub on_err: ChildOutcomeAction,\n    pub on_cancel: ChildOutcomeAction,\n    pub on_panic: ChildOutcomeAction,\n    pub aggregate: AggregateStrategy,\n}\n\n#[derive(Clone, Copy, Debug)]\npub enum ChildOutcomeAction {\n    Ignore,\n    CancelSiblings,\n    EscalateToParent,\n}\n\n#[derive(Clone, Copy, Debug)]\npub enum AggregateStrategy {\n    MaxSeverity,\n    // Future: more structured aggregation for supervision/actors\n}\n```\n\nImplementation sketch:\n- On child completion, apply `on_*` action to decide whether to request cancellation on siblings.\n- Region close computes final outcome according to `aggregate`.\n\n## Edge Cases to Specify\n- If multiple children fail with different severities, aggregation returns the max severity.\n- If a child panics:\n  - Phase 0 default: treat as `Outcome::Panicked` and (optionally) cancel siblings.\n- Finalizer outcomes:\n  - If finalizers can panic, how is this recorded? (Prefer: capture as Panicked outcome and continue running remaining finalizers.)\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- `Policy` exists and is used by:\n  - join combinator\n  - region close logic\n  - fail-fast cancellation (if enabled)\n- Unit tests cover:\n  - aggregation behavior\n  - fail-fast sibling cancellation triggers\n  - determinism under repeated runs\n\n## Testing\n- E2E: join two tasks where one errors; with fail-fast policy, other is cancelled and drained.\n\n","notes":"Implemented Policy surface aligned to formal semantics + API skeleton. Changes:\n- `src/types/policy.rs`: `PolicyAction::CancelSiblings(CancelReason)` and `AggregateDecision::{Cancelled(CancelReason), Panicked(PanicPayload)}`; `FailFast` only cancels siblings on Err/Panic (not Cancelled); cancel aggregation strengthens deterministically.\n- `src/runtime/state.rs`: added `RuntimeState::apply_policy_on_child_outcome` hook that applies policy and requests sibling cancellation.\n- `src/combinator/join.rs`: added `aggregate_outcomes(policy, outcomes)` helper to make join semantics explicitly policy-driven.\n- Tests: policy unit tests (ordering + aggregation), and runtime-state sibling cancellation tests.\n\nGates: cargo fmt --check, cargo check --all-targets, cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings, cargo test all pass.","status":"closed","priority":0,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-01-16T07:14:26.415906021Z","created_by":"Dicklesworthstone","updated_at":"2026-01-16T14:03:42.526006370Z","closed_at":"2026-01-16T14:03:42.526006370Z","close_reason":"Policy implementation complete per notes. FailFast and CollectAll policies implemented with proper aggregation. Unit tests pass. All quality gates pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-37o9s","depends_on_id":"asupersync-2lbjg","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:42Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-37o9s","depends_on_id":"asupersync-3a1mq","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:42Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-37o9s","depends_on_id":"asupersync-goeck","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:42Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
